For

    auto foo = T{0};

to work, `T` has to be a *simple-type-specifier*.

From the [C++11 Standard/5.2.3 Explicit type conversion (functional notation)/3](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/expr.type.conv#3)

&gt; Similarly, a [*simple-type-specifier*](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/dcl.type.simple#nt:simple-type-specifier) or *typename-specifier* followed by a [*braced-init-list*](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/temp.res#nt:typename-specifier) creates a temporary object of the specified type direct-list-initialized ([[dcl.init.list]](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/dcl.init.list)) with the specified [*braced-init-list*](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/temp.res#nt:typename-specifier), and its value is that temporary object as a prvalue.

If you see the definition of [*simple-type-specifier*](https://timsong-cpp.github.io/cppwp/n3337/dcl.type.simple#nt:simple-type-specifier), `unsigned int` is not one of them.

You can use any of the following:

    auto foo = 0U;
    auto foo = (unsigned int)0;
    auto foo = static_cast&lt;unsigned int&gt;(0);

